        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator will be optimized for the continuum in three basebands, using TDM mode. This will ensure that the least amount of molecular emission is picked up as contamination. The last spectral window will be tuned to 13CO 1-0 with a spectral resolution of 0.3 km/s. The latter will allow us to track the disk rotation (expected to be 2 km/s wide) by resolving it with 6 velocity elements.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The chosen angular resolution of 0.08 arcseconds will be able to resolve down to scales of 35 AU, and thus resolve even the smaller disk sizes. Given the largest angular scale (1 arcsecond), this allows one to place at least 3-4 beams across each of the disks, which are an estimated 150 AU in scale, much smaller than the maximum recoverable scale of 1 arcsecond. This is an important part as the combination of resolving the disk while also not filtering out the outer disk will allow us to derive very accurate inclination from the imaged elongations.

We are aware that this mode uses the very longest baselines. The team participated in the EOC campaign and can be called upon to assist in optimizing the calibration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The sensitivity we would like to achieve is 25 microJansky/beam (beam = 0.08"), equalling a total of 1.1 hours of ALMA time. Using the eSMA detections, all disks are expected to peak at 130 milliJansky/beam (beam = 0.25", see van Kempen et al., 2009). Correcting for the beam difference, this translates to an expected peak flux of 800 microjansky/beam, thus a S/N &gt; 25.  This allows us to detect even the weaker disk components. 

For the line, we expect to heavily resolve out the detection made by the SMA. However, the line sensitivity for the continuum integration time equals 3 mJy. Given the difference in beam sizes and assuming a filtering of 90%, we expect to obtain a 2.5sigma detection in 13CO per 0.5 km/s bin. Spatial smoothing to 0.2" will allow us to detect both sides of a 150 AU disk and make a map of the kinematics using a S/N = 6 per channel. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
