    <prp:abstract>The formation of disks in the embedded stage of star formation is complicated. Recent ALMA observations revealed that even isolated sources show much more structure than previously assumed. However, most stars do not form in isolation, but in small clusters with close (&lt;1,000 AU) neighbours that affect their formation. Other ALMA results showed one case where disks that were formed did not align, even though the protostars interacted heavily. This combination of results poses a new question: how do disks align in clustered star formation? This is important as disk alignment traces outflow direction and thus reveals how angular momentum for the entire core is shedded. Do the alignment of disks in clustered star formation depend on neighbours? or not at all? a combination that depends on stellar mass?
Using the very longest baselines, we propose to study the newly formed embedded disks in NGC 2071, an embedded mini-cluster forming at least 5, and likely more than 7, solar-mass stars. Using the sensitivity in Band 3 and the very longest baselines, we can resolve disk structure at a resolution of less than 30 AU, much better than the known extend of these disks (~150 AU).</prp:abstract>
